joke: OAuth is secure because neither the users or the developers understand how it works.
Netflix is a monitoring system and an operation platform that occasionally streams video.
Microservices are just distributed monoliths with better marketing and worse debugging.
The most secure part of any encryption system is the developers belief that their users will follow best practices.
AWS isn't a cloud provider, it's a creative writing workshop where all assignments involve explaining unexpected billing charges.
Docker's greatest achievement was convincing developers that packaging an entire operating system with your app is the minimalist approach.
The cloud is just someone else's computer that goes down during your demo.
Byzantine fault tolerance is preparing for scenarios where your servers are actively plotting against you.
CAP theorem says you can have two out of three guarantees, but in production, you're lucky to get one.
Race conditions are the quantum mechanics of programming, things are in superposition until somebody observes the bug.
"Eventual consistency" means "it's wrong now, but will be right after the demo."
Legacy code is a euphemism for "it makes money so we can't delete it."
The only thing learned from incident postmortems is how to better cover your tracks next time.
Heisenbug: when observing the bug fixes it, and not observing it crashes production.
RESTful API: Because sometimes you need six different endpoints to retrieve data that used to be in one SQL query.
The term "fully automated CI/CD pipeline" actually means "Jenkins is going to break at 4:59 PM on Friday."
The P in PHP stands for "Please stop using this for new projects."
NoSQL is for developers who found learning SQL too difficult, so they invented something more complicated instead.
Python developers brag about readability while writing list comprehensions that look like someone's cat walked on the keyboard.
"Database sharding" is architecturespeak for "Our original design was terrible but we have too much VC money to start over."
Pair programming is a technique where two developers can create the same bugs twice as expensively.
All "distributed systems" really are just Postgres doing the heavy lifting.
True 10x devs are engineers who know when not to build things.
The main use case for Kubernetes is to keep your infra team too busy to notice that your app could run on a single VM.
WebSockets exist solely to create race conditions too subtle to reproduce in your local environment.
Monorepos are what happens when your organization is too dysfunctional to coordinate across multiple repositories.
The primary function of JIRA is to generate enough metrics to justify the continued employment of project managers.
Kafka is just a message queue with enough complexity to ensure your entire data engineering team is too busy debugging to notice they could have used a database.
Apache Spark exists to make Hadoop seem user friendly by comparison.
Elasticsearch is where developers go when they want the performance of NoSQL with the query complexity of SQL and the operational stability of neither.
Redis is a database for developers who want the thrill of losing all their data when the server restarts.
RabbitMQ is what you implement before realizing that your actual scaling problem is your architecture, not your message queue.
"Real time data processing" means your batch jobs now fail in real-time instead of overnight.
"Schema on write" vs "schema on read" is just choosing whether you want your data quality problems now or later.
Prometheus is an excellent tool for collecting metrics about all the ways your system is failing without giving you enough context to fix anything.
Grafana dashboards are beautiful visualizations of data that nobody looks at until after the production outage.
GitLab CI is what happens when your version control system gets tired of just storing code and decides it wants to break your builds too.
Terraform is infrastructure-as-code for people who want their infrastructure to break in new and exciting ways with each version upgrade.
Salesforce is just Excel with a significantly higher price tag and more consultants.
Datadog is what you implement when you want to pay more for monitoring than the actual infrastructure being monitored.
Your observability stack is probably so comprehensive that you now spend more time monitoring your monitoring systems than your actual application.
Code comments are like middle management, when they're good, they clarify everything, and when they're bad, they actively mislead while adding no value.
Azure DevOps: making you feel productive right up until the mystery pipeline failure eats your weekend.
GCP's console is designed to ensure you can never find the same feature twice, keeping cloud engineers in a constant state of humility.
Most incident response plans are so detailed it has everything except what actually goes wrong in production.
Production hotfixes are usually bugs you haven't had time to properly document yet.
Canary deployments are just a way to ensure that only a subset of your customers hate you at any given time.
Database migrations are just professionally sanctioned games of Russian roulette with production data.
Containers solve the "works on my machine" problem by making it everyone's problem.
Zero downtime deployments are technically accurate, the downtime comes after the deployment when everything breaks.
